---
import '../../styles/global.css';
import LessonLayout from '../../layouts/LessonLayout.astro';
import LessonHeader from '../../components/LessonHeader.astro';
import LessonNav from '../../components/LessonNav.astro';
import InsightBox from '../../components/InsightBox.astro';
import TagBadge from '../../components/TagBadge.astro';
import Formula from '../../components/Formula.astro';
import SemanticMapDemo from '../../components/demos/SemanticMapDemo.astro';
---

<LessonLayout title="Measuring Closeness" lessonNumber="1.2" section="Embeddings">

    <LessonHeader lessonNumber="1.2" title="Measuring Closeness" description="If meaning is distance, you need a way to measure it. Cosine similarity reads the angle between two meanings.">
        <TagBadge variant="math">math</TagBadge>
        <TagBadge variant="default">9 min read</TagBadge>
    </LessonHeader>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Drag the question and watch the nearest meanings light up.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Last lesson, meaning became a map of points. The natural next question: given a question dropped
            anywhere on that map, which passages are closest? Grab the coral dot below and move it. The three
            nearest passages light up, and a closeness number updates as you go. Drag it into the dog corner and
            the dog words win; drag it toward the car corner and they take over.
        </p>

        <SemanticMapDemo />

        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            That is retrieval in miniature. The question is a point, every passage is a point, and we keep the
            ones that sit nearest. The rest of this lesson is about how to put a real number on "nearest".
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Why the angle, not the raw distance.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The obvious move is straight-line distance, the gap between two points. It works on the toy map, but
            it has a flaw in real embeddings: longer texts tend to produce longer vectors (points further from
            the origin), so a chatty passage can look "far" just for being long, even when it is about exactly
            the right thing. Length should not decide meaning.
        </p>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            So instead of distance we read direction. Picture an arrow from the origin out to each point. Two
            texts about the same thing point the same way, whatever their length. The standard measure is
            <strong>cosine similarity</strong>: it reads the angle between the two arrows and ignores how long
            they are.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-white border border-mt-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            <p class="mb-1"><span class="font-semibold text-mt-text">same direction</span> (angle 0) &rarr; cosine <span class="font-mono text-mt-green">1</span>, very similar.</p>
            <p class="mb-1"><span class="font-semibold text-mt-text">at a right angle</span> (angle 90) &rarr; cosine <span class="font-mono text-mt-muted">0</span>, unrelated.</p>
            <p class="mb-0"><span class="font-semibold text-mt-text">opposite direction</span> (angle 180) &rarr; cosine <span class="font-mono text-mt-rose">-1</span>, opposite meaning.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">The formula, then a worked number.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Cosine similarity is a short recipe. Multiply the two vectors piece by piece and add up the results
            (that sum is the dot product). Then divide by each vector's length, to cancel out how long they are.
        </p>
        <Formula caption="dot product on top, the two vector lengths on the bottom">
            <span class="var">cos</span>(<span class="var">a</span>, <span class="var">b</span>) <span class="op">=</span> ( <span class="var">a</span> &middot; <span class="var">b</span> ) <span class="op">/</span> ( |<span class="var">a</span>| &times; |<span class="var">b</span>| )
        </Formula>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Take two tiny vectors, <span class="font-mono text-xs">a = (3, 4)</span> for the question and
            <span class="font-mono text-xs">b = (4, 3)</span> for a passage. Top line, the dot product:
            <span class="font-mono text-xs">3&times;4 + 4&times;3 = 12 + 12 = 24</span>. Bottom line, the lengths:
            each is <span class="font-mono text-xs">&radic;(3&sup2; + 4&sup2;) = &radic;25 = 5</span>, so the
            bottom is <span class="font-mono text-xs">5 &times; 5 = 25</span>.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-white border border-mt-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            <p class="mb-1 font-mono">cos(a, b) = 24 / 25 = <span class="text-mt-green">0.96</span></p>
            <p class="text-mt-muted text-xs">Close to 1, so these two nearly point the same way: a strong match.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Now double the passage to <span class="font-mono text-xs">b = (8, 6)</span>, twice as long. The dot
            product doubles to <span class="font-mono text-xs">48</span> and the bottom doubles too
            (<span class="font-mono text-xs">5 &times; 10 = 50</span>), so the score stays
            <span class="font-mono text-xs">48 / 50 = 0.96</span>. Length changed, the verdict did not. That is
            exactly the property we wanted.
        </p>
        <InsightBox>
            <p class="text-sm">Cosine similarity scores meaning by <strong>direction</strong>, on a scale from
            1 (same) through 0 (unrelated) to -1 (opposite). Because it divides out length, a long passage and a
            short one are judged on what they say, not how much.</p>
        </InsightBox>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Key takeaways</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">1</span></div><p class="text-sm">Retrieval ranks passages by closeness to the question, both treated as points in the embedding space.</p></div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">2</span></div><p class="text-sm">Cosine similarity reads the angle between two vectors: 1 is same direction, 0 is unrelated, -1 is opposite.</p></div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">3</span></div><p class="text-sm">It divides out vector length, so a passage is scored on meaning, not on how long it happens to be.</p></div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <LessonNav
        prevHref="/embeddings/meaning-as-geometry" prevLabel="Prev: Meaning as Geometry"
        nextHref="/embeddings/chunking" nextLabel="Next: Chunking a Document"
    />

</LessonLayout>
